Data Description¶

The dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Context¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

# Dropping the columns which doesn't seems of much importance

data_model = data.drop(['ZIP Code', 'ID'], axis=1)

# Performing Manual Hot Encoding to drop Education column
data_model['Education_Undergrad'] = data.apply(lambda x : 1 if x['Education'] == 1 else 0, axis=1)
data_model['Education_Graduate'] = data.apply(lambda x : 1 if x['Education'] == 2 else 0, axis=1)
data_model.drop('Education', axis=1, inplace=True)

In [56]:
## defining a function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_confusion_matrix( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
    
# defining a function to print out model results
def print_results(regression_model, x_test, y_test, y_predict):
    print("Training accuracy:",regression_model.score(x_train,y_train))  
    print()
    print("Testing Accuracy:",regression_model.score(x_test, y_test))
    print()
    print("Recall:",recall_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print("Precision:",precision_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print("F1 Score:",f1_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print("Roc Auc Score:",roc_auc_score(y_test,y_predict))
    print()
    print('Confusion Matrix')
    print(draw_confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict))

# defining a function to draw area under the curve
def draw_curve(y_test,x_test):
    logit_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, regression_model.predict(x_test))
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, regression_model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1])
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='Logistic Regression (area = %0.2f)' % logit_roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.savefig('Log_ROC')
    plt.show()

Give conclusion related to the Business understanding of your model? (5 marks)¶

6. Business Understanding of the model¶

Insights¶

  • Fields like ID and ZIP are of not much relavance and doesn't contribute anything in the model

  • Categorical Variables
    • Credit Card and Online fields do not seems to have much impact on the target variable (Personal Loan)
    • CD Account seems to have a good effect on the target variable (Personal Loan)
    • Securities Account seems to have a minor effect on the target variable (Personal Loan)
    • Education also has a minor effect on the target variable (Personal Loan).
    • Family does have a very minor effect on the target variable.

  • Continuous Variables
    • Mortgage has a minor effect on the target variable. (Personal Loan)
    • Income has a strong effect on the target variable. (Personal Loan)
    • Age and Experience show some minor effect on the target variable (Personal Loan)
    • CCAvg does have an effect on the target variable.

Conclusions¶

  • Accuracy: ~96% (Although accuracy is not always a good measure, we will look at other attributes)
  • Type I error = 11 (FP - Customers who were predicted to offer a loan while they didn't actually get it) , Type II error = 48 (FN - Customers who are predicted not to offer a loan while they actually got it)
  • Recall (Out of total customers who accepted loan our prediction to offer loan is at): ~63%
  • Precision (Out of total customers who were offered loan from our model while people who actually took loan is at): ~88%
  • Precision is high and Recall is not that high, still making this a good model as F-Score is: ~73%
  • Area under the Curve is ~81% also shows that this is a good model.
